title: For Sale:  Makarov East German 9mm
postcontent:
Like new, fired only 40 times. East German Makarov from 1961 that is collectible and one of the best units made. 

Includes a NEW shoulder holster for concealed carry and 50 rounds of ammo

Includes 2 sets of grips (Originals and larger Grips)

Must have a CCW or permit to buy

Mine is 1961 AT

The Ernst Thaelman factory in Suhl, Thueringen made what are considered by some to be the finest pre-fall-of-the-Berlin Wall Makarovs. The finish is nice, the fit and machining is of quality you'd expect from a German shop, and they shoot like a dream. Almost all that came into this country had already seen service, so their quality varies by how they were treated by the person who carried them. Nonetheless, most have more holster wear than bore wear. They occasionally still pop up at dealers and at gun shows. If you can get them for a good price, these are the ones to buy.
Markings on them include a letter 'y' with a circle of dots, which some Russian folks think stands for for uchebneii or "training". This would be strange for a German pistol, but we haven't heard any other explanations. 
Note that this table is not complete and there appears to be a sequential pattern, so don't panic if yours doesn't fit into the ones listed. 
East German production codes
(not a complete list)

Production year	Letter Code
1958	S
1959	J, K, L, N, U
1960	B, F, G, H, M, T
1961	AP*,AR, AS, AQ, AT, AU, AV, AW, AX, AY, AZ
1962	BR, BT, BU, BV, BW, BX, BY, BZ
1963	DA, DB, DE, DF, DH, DK, DL, DP, BO, BP
1964	ES, ET, EV, EX, EZ
1965	ER, FB, FH, FF

To assemble, simply attach the receiver to the stock, insert the barrel, screw on the barrel nut and you're ready to fire. In seconds, you'll have the security of a semi-automatic rifle without the bulk and weight of a full size firearm.

The Henry U.S. Survival rifle features a steel barrel that is covered in a tough ABS plastic and then coated in Teflon. This unique barrel design allows the gun to balance properly and remain lightweight, yet withstand tens of thousands of rounds. The entire receiver is also coated in Teflon, making the Henry U.S. Survival rifle the most weather-resistant of any AR-7 ever made. As an added feature, the receiver rib is now grooved for easy installation of a scope.

The rifle is capable of feeding both standard and high velocity .22 Long Rifle ammunition. Available in black, silver or camouflage finishes.


The Henry US Survival comes in black cardboard case with plastic carrying handle.

title: For Sale:  East German Makarov LIKE NEW from 1961
postcontent:
Beautiful East German Makarov from 1961 fired less than 40 times. These guns were used by the German army because you can field strip them, clean and reassemble in less than 3 min. It was still in the box when I bought it a few years back.

I added Pearce grips (Larger) and the original ones are included. Must have Permit or CCW

The info on this gun is below. Mine is 61 AT Version. A great collectible or carry gun.

The Ernst Thaelman factory in Suhl, Thueringen made what are considered by some to be the finest pre-fall-of-the-Berlin Wall Makarovs. The finish is nice, the fit and machining is of quality you'd expect from a German shop, and they shoot like a dream. Almost all that came into this country had already seen service, so their quality varies by how they were treated by the person who carried them. Nonetheless, most have more holster wear than bore wear. They occasionally still pop up at dealers and at gun shows. If you can get them for a good price, these are the ones to buy.
Markings on them include a letter 'y' with a circle of dots, which some Russian folks think stands for for uchebneii or "training". This would be strange for a German pistol, but we haven't heard any other explanations. 
Note that this table is not complete and there appears to be a sequential pattern, so don't panic if yours doesn't fit into the ones listed. 
East German production codes
(not a complete list)

Production year	Letter Code
1958	S
1959	J, K, L, N, U
1960	B, F, G, H, M, T
1961	AP*,AR, AS, AQ, AT, AU, AV, AW, AX, AY, AZ
1962	BR, BT, BU, BV, BW, BX, BY, BZ
1963	DA, DB, DE, DF, DH, DK, DL, DP, BO, BP
1964	ES, ET, EV, EX, EZ
1965	ER, FB, FH, FF

This is a very nice, very powerful gun.  It was the official Russian sidearm.  Most that you will find are re-arsenaled.  They were originally parkerized and when re-arsenaled they were just dipped in caustic blue.  Those have a rough black appearance.  Not very appealling.  This one is parkerized but not re-arsenaled.  I have done research and am positive of this fact.  Comes with one original clip and one aftermarket clip that works very well.  I have tested this clip extensively and have had no issues.  Comes with original barrel, all matching numbers.  The original barrel has very slight corrosion near the chamber but shoots fine.  I have a new barrel installed on the gun right now (less than 50 rounds fired through it and then cleaned well). the original grips on this gun are the nicest ones i've seen. There were only 200,000-225,000 of these guns made.  Some day they will be very collectable.  Comes with a box of quality 70 rds ammo.  Gun, 2 barrels, 2 clips and ammo = $280.00

Jim REDACTED

title: For Sale:  Browning BDA .380
postcontent:
The Browning BDA 380 pistol was introduced in 1980 or so as a compact and lightweight pistol for police and civilian use. The gun was manufactured in Italy under contract from FN Herstal (Belgium) and marketed as FN model 140DA (in Europe) or Browning BDA 380 (in USA). Some sources said that BDA 380 is a copy of Beretta 84, but close inspection shows some differences (i.e. Beretta 84 has frame mounted safety while BDA 380 has slide mounted safety). The manufacture of the BDA 380 was ceased circa 1997. It was adopted by Belgian police.

The BDA 380 is a blowback operated, double action semi automatic pistol. It has aluminium alloy frame and steel slide. Ambidextrous slide mounted safety switch disconnects the trigger from the hammer when engaged. The pistol featured low profile fixed sightst and was available in either polished steel or blued finish, with wooden grip panels.

The gun deserved good reputation as reliable and comfortable to fire.

http://www.blueridgeoutdoorsports.com/Fire_Arms.html

title: For Sale/Trade:  Meriden 12 Ga. Single Original Sears Shotgun Pre J.C. Higgins
postcontent: 32" barrel shows some pitting, but shiny. 48 ¼" overall length. Says choke bored. Muzzle measures .665. Front sight has been re soldered on. Pictures show it's condition, after all it is almost 100 years old. This is the original name used on the "Sears and Roebuck" guns until 1918 when "Meriden" went out of business and "Sears" started selling under the "J.C Higgins" name. Pretty cool old historical shoot able Americana. Open to trades. Or $120.
